00:04:35.580 --> 00:04:39.390
Citizenship is one of
the defining and dividing

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:43.230
issues of our time,
and it means far more

00:04:43.230 --> 00:04:46.110
than formal membership
in a nation state

00:04:46.110 --> 00:04:48.780
or the possession of a passport.

00:04:48.780 --> 00:04:51.210
Citizenship informs
participation

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:53.470
in the social,
economic, cultural,

00:04:53.470 --> 00:04:55.750
and political
activities of a nation,

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:59.670
and it is a critical
component of belonging.

00:04:59.670 --> 00:05:04.290
With more than 65 million people
displaced from their homes

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:07.980
and with nationalism on the
rise in many parts of the world,

00:05:07.980 --> 00:05:11.130
citizenship has taken
on even greater salience

00:05:11.130 --> 00:05:13.230
in our current moment.

00:05:13.230 --> 00:05:18.210
That said, some might ask,
but why devote a conference

00:05:18.210 --> 00:05:21.420
to citizenship and gender?

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:24.630
Radcliffe's thematic initiative,
exploring citizenship,

00:05:24.630 --> 00:05:28.530
is timed in part to anticipate
the centennial of National

00:05:28.530 --> 00:05:31.590
Women's Suffrage in
2020, since we thought

00:05:31.590 --> 00:05:35.490
it was important to embed that
milestone within the larger

00:05:35.490 --> 00:05:38.530
context of citizenship rights.

00:05:38.530 --> 00:05:41.040
But even if at least
some American women

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:45.420
have enjoyed full political
franchise for almost a century,

00:05:45.420 --> 00:05:48.000
the link between
gender and rights

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:50.490
and the rights and
obligations of citizenship

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:53.510
is hardly a settled issue.

00:05:53.510 --> 00:05:56.540
Still today, gender has
an important bearing

00:05:56.540 --> 00:06:00.900
on many aspects of citizenship
and belonging around the world.

00:06:00.900 --> 00:06:03.710
Some of the most fundamental
citizenship rights

00:06:03.710 --> 00:06:07.460
continue to be negotiated
and redrawn along gender

00:06:07.460 --> 00:06:11.570
lines with real
impact on real people.

00:06:11.570 --> 00:06:14.300
Many of us are aware of the
very limited political voting

00:06:14.300 --> 00:06:17.930
rights afforded women in
countries like Saudi Arabia,

00:06:17.930 --> 00:06:22.010
but it is notable that even in a
wealthy, institutionally strong

00:06:22.010 --> 00:06:24.830
democracy like
Switzerland, women only

00:06:24.830 --> 00:06:27.230
gained the right to vote
in federal elections

00:06:27.230 --> 00:06:30.430
as recently as 1971.

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:35.060
And it wasn't until 1990 that
Switzerland's highest court

00:06:35.060 --> 00:06:38.270
ordered the last holdout
canton to stop barring women

00:06:38.270 --> 00:06:41.120
from voting on local issues.

00:06:41.120 --> 00:06:43.940
Beyond voting rights,
women around the world

00:06:43.940 --> 00:06:47.420
are far more likely than men
to earn their livelihoods

00:06:47.420 --> 00:06:50.630
in domestic work, often
as migrant laborers,

00:06:50.630 --> 00:06:55.010
and often without the benefit
of legal and social protections.

00:06:55.010 --> 00:06:58.670
Moreover, according to the
United Nations, only about half

00:06:58.670 --> 00:07:03.230
of married women worldwide can
freely make personal decisions

00:07:03.230 --> 00:07:05.840
about their health
care, sexual relations,

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:08.290
and contraceptive use.

00:07:08.290 --> 00:07:12.160
Even here in the United States,
certain basic legal rights

00:07:12.160 --> 00:07:17.050
still reflect gender inequality
and traditional gender norms.

00:07:17.050 --> 00:07:20.320
Not even a year ago,
the US Supreme Court

00:07:20.320 --> 00:07:24.370
struck down sections of the
Immigration and Nationality Act

00:07:24.370 --> 00:07:28.060
under which unmarried American
mothers and fathers living

00:07:28.060 --> 00:07:31.600
abroad had to meet
different standards in order

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:36.100
for their children to acquire
US citizenship at birth.

00:07:36.100 --> 00:07:38.620
Under the old law,
in certain instances,

00:07:38.620 --> 00:07:41.860
a US citizen mother could
transmit citizenship

00:07:41.860 --> 00:07:45.100
to her child, while a father
in the exact same situation

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:47.620
could not, and vice versa.

00:07:47.620 --> 00:07:49.970
In a nearly unanimous decision--

00:07:49.970 --> 00:07:52.570
those are rare-- the
Supreme Court ruled

00:07:52.570 --> 00:07:55.060
that these disparate
requirements violated

00:07:55.060 --> 00:07:57.760
the Fifth Amendment's
Equal Protection Clause.

00:07:57.760 --> 00:08:00.670
The court urged Congress
to remedy the issue,

00:08:00.670 --> 00:08:03.280
and in the interim, the
residency requirement

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:05.590
that had previously
applied to fathers

00:08:05.590 --> 00:08:08.050
would apply to all parents.

00:08:08.050 --> 00:08:11.740
Writing for the Court,
Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg

00:08:11.740 --> 00:08:15.400
called the differentiation
between fathers and mothers

00:08:15.400 --> 00:08:17.470
"stunningly anachronistic."

00:08:17.470 --> 00:08:20.500
And she argued that it
reflected-- and I quote her--

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:24.550
"two once habitual but now
untenable assumptions."

00:08:24.550 --> 00:08:26.530
One assumption
was that a husband

00:08:26.530 --> 00:08:28.960
is the principal
figure in a household,

00:08:28.960 --> 00:08:31.780
in charge of wife and children.

00:08:31.780 --> 00:08:34.809
The second and related
notion was that outside

00:08:34.809 --> 00:08:37.080
of a marriage--
and I quote her--

00:08:37.080 --> 00:08:40.870
"an unwed mother is the
natural and sole guardian."

00:08:40.870 --> 00:08:43.570
These stereotypes lead
to an intricate system

00:08:43.570 --> 00:08:46.120
of gender differentiated
regulations

00:08:46.120 --> 00:08:49.870
that played a critical role in
US citizenship and nationality

00:08:49.870 --> 00:08:53.580
law until 2017.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:57.100
I will share just one more brief
illustration of the interplay

00:08:57.100 --> 00:08:59.740
between gender and citizenship.

00:08:59.740 --> 00:09:02.440
As all of us have
experienced in our lives,

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:06.250
we frequently need personal
identification documents,

00:09:06.250 --> 00:09:08.830
whether for employment,
for school enrollment,

00:09:08.830 --> 00:09:11.650
for health care, for housing.

00:09:11.650 --> 00:09:15.220
These IDs typically
indicate our gender,

00:09:15.220 --> 00:09:17.740
and herein lies the problem.

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:21.260
For many transgender
people across this country,

00:09:21.260 --> 00:09:24.370
the process of
updating and using IDs

00:09:24.370 --> 00:09:26.770
can be fraught with challenges.

00:09:26.770 --> 00:09:29.290
Potential difficulties
include denied

00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:32.200
access to public
and private services

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:34.540
and the risk of verbal
harassment or even

00:09:34.540 --> 00:09:36.190
physical violence.

00:09:36.190 --> 00:09:39.280
And in states with
voter ID laws,

00:09:39.280 --> 00:09:41.890
the lack of usable
identification

00:09:41.890 --> 00:09:44.410
could deprive citizens
of their basic right

00:09:44.410 --> 00:09:47.440
to participate in our democracy.

00:09:47.440 --> 00:09:50.830
According to research by the
National Center for Transgender

00:09:50.830 --> 00:09:57.550
Equality, as of 2015,
68% of transgender people

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:01.390
lack even one form of ID
with their preferred name

00:10:01.390 --> 00:10:02.740
and gender.

00:10:02.740 --> 00:10:06.100
Only 11% had their
preferred name and gender

00:10:06.100 --> 00:10:08.650
on all of their IDs.

00:10:08.650 --> 00:10:12.070
And correcting this is not just
a simple matter of heading down

00:10:12.070 --> 00:10:14.410
to the motor vehicle registry.

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:16.720
In February, the American
Civil Liberties Union

00:10:16.720 --> 00:10:20.200
filed suit, challenging
an Alabama law that

00:10:20.200 --> 00:10:23.890
requires transgender
people to show proof

00:10:23.890 --> 00:10:27.400
of gender-confirming surgery
before the state would

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:31.030
issue a driver's license
that reflects their identity.

00:10:31.030 --> 00:10:35.560
Eight other states have similar
rules, according to the ACLU.

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:38.890
Not all transgender
people want or can

00:10:38.890 --> 00:10:41.470
afford this type of surgery.

00:10:41.470 --> 00:10:45.340
But more broadly, the ACLU
contends that a medical

00:10:45.340 --> 00:10:50.050
procedure cannot be a
prerequisite for acquiring

00:10:50.050 --> 00:10:52.950
a government-issued ID.

00:10:52.950 --> 00:10:55.530
To complicate matters
further, Alabama

00:10:55.530 --> 00:10:59.760
is one of 34 states in the
country that either requires

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:03.030
or requests voters to show
acceptable identification

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:04.530
at the polls.

00:11:04.530 --> 00:11:09.480
This creates a very real risk
that transgendered individuals

00:11:09.480 --> 00:11:14.380
who present incongruent IDs will
be denied their voting rights.

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:16.680
So I hope these
examples illustrate

00:11:16.680 --> 00:11:20.280
that gender continues to
intersect with citizenship

00:11:20.280 --> 00:11:22.740
in very tangible ways.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:28.260
Before us today is a totally
complex, multifaceted topic,

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:31.500
