00:14:19.860 --> 00:14:20.960
brilliant thinkers.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:24.080
I'm just going to right off
the top introduce them briefly.

00:14:24.080 --> 00:14:28.160
There are more detailed
bios in your programs

00:14:28.160 --> 00:14:31.040
that do them justice.

00:14:31.040 --> 00:14:33.620
I'll introduce them in the
order in which I understand

00:14:33.620 --> 00:14:34.980
everybody is going to speak.

00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:36.680
Kari Hong.

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:38.780
First, she is an
Assistant Professor

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:41.900
of Law at Boston
College Law School.

00:14:41.900 --> 00:14:46.250
Martha Jones, the Society
of Black Alumni Presidential

00:14:46.250 --> 00:14:49.640
Professor and Professor of
History at Johns Hopkins

00:14:49.640 --> 00:14:50.270
University.

00:14:50.270 --> 00:14:54.560
And Tali Mendelberg, John
Work Garrett Professor

00:14:54.560 --> 00:14:58.220
of Politics and Director of
the Program on Inequality

00:14:58.220 --> 00:15:01.580
at the Mamdouha S. Bobst--

00:15:01.580 --> 00:15:02.960
how'd I do--

00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:08.960
Center for Peace and Justice
at Princeton University.

00:15:08.960 --> 00:15:12.390
The topic for this
panel is rights, duties,

00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:14.840
and responsibilities.

00:15:14.840 --> 00:15:17.970
And I'm going to keep my
opening remarks very brief.

00:15:17.970 --> 00:15:19.700
I think it's
entirely appropriate

00:15:19.700 --> 00:15:24.590
to begin a panel on citizenship
with a discussion of rights

00:15:24.590 --> 00:15:26.540
and duties and
responsibilities, because these

00:15:26.540 --> 00:15:29.030
are at the core of
what it means to be

00:15:29.030 --> 00:15:32.600
a citizen in a liberal
democratic society.

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:35.780
As citizens, we're
granted certain freedoms,

00:15:35.780 --> 00:15:39.620
but we also face
expectations about how

00:15:39.620 --> 00:15:44.270
we are to engage with each other
and with our political system.

00:15:44.270 --> 00:15:46.010
The first words in
the US constitution--

00:15:46.010 --> 00:15:46.850
I love to do this.

00:15:46.850 --> 00:15:50.960
What is the first word of the
Constitution of the United

00:15:50.960 --> 00:15:51.500
States?

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:52.440
- We.

00:15:52.440 --> 00:15:52.940
- Yes.

00:15:52.940 --> 00:15:57.020
And we don't say we enough
anymore in this country.

00:15:57.020 --> 00:16:00.460
The first words are
"We the people."

00:16:00.460 --> 00:16:04.505
And they convey something
very important of who

00:16:04.505 --> 00:16:06.020
we think of ourselves.

00:16:06.020 --> 00:16:07.850
They speak of the
obligations we have

00:16:07.850 --> 00:16:11.060
to each other and our nation.

00:16:11.060 --> 00:16:14.660
Democracy fails when
citizens don't exercise

00:16:14.660 --> 00:16:17.000
their duties and
responsibilities, including

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:17.960
voting and organizing.

00:16:17.960 --> 00:16:20.630
And if I may say
so, this is a year

00:16:20.630 --> 00:16:23.120
when I think it's
especially important

00:16:23.120 --> 00:16:28.890
to think about our duties to
engage in those activities.

00:16:28.890 --> 00:16:31.220
I want to raise at the
start the importance

00:16:31.220 --> 00:16:35.180
of thinking about rights,
duties, and responsibilities

00:16:35.180 --> 00:16:36.780
through many analytical lenses.

00:16:36.780 --> 00:16:39.320
And I think the wonderful
thing about this panel

00:16:39.320 --> 00:16:43.340
is that's exactly what
they will do today.

00:16:43.340 --> 00:16:48.620
Our focus is on
gender, but I think

00:16:48.620 --> 00:16:53.210
we also want to keep in mind
the dynamics of citizenship

00:16:53.210 --> 00:16:56.150
and of gendered
citizenship, and how

00:16:56.150 --> 00:16:58.610
they are affected
by race, class,

00:16:58.610 --> 00:17:01.220
immigration status,
and a variety

00:17:01.220 --> 00:17:04.310
of other social factors.

00:17:04.310 --> 00:17:08.119
Class is a framework that
in many prosperous parts

00:17:08.119 --> 00:17:11.150
of our society can be
uncomfortable approaching.

00:17:11.150 --> 00:17:14.210
And yet it is clear that
socioeconomic status

00:17:14.210 --> 00:17:16.250
and growing income
inequality are

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:21.470
powerful forces shaping the
contours of American society

00:17:21.470 --> 00:17:22.700
and politics.

00:17:22.700 --> 00:17:26.750
Class dynamics often interact
with gender dynamics.

00:17:26.750 --> 00:17:29.700
The persistent gender
wage gap, for example,

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:32.390
means that many women find
themselves more economically

00:17:32.390 --> 00:17:34.400
vulnerable than
their male peers,

00:17:34.400 --> 00:17:37.760
and are thus barred from
fully equal participation,

00:17:37.760 --> 00:17:40.460
not only because of
lingering sexism,

00:17:40.460 --> 00:17:43.700
but also because of
the hidden and not so

00:17:43.700 --> 00:17:47.930
hidden injuries of class.

00:17:47.930 --> 00:17:51.770
I would note the teachers
strike in Oklahoma

00:17:51.770 --> 00:17:53.690
as an example of this.

00:17:53.690 --> 00:17:56.880
And it's worth
noting that about 75%

00:17:56.880 --> 00:18:01.110
of the people in that
underpaid profession are women.

00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:03.150
In the conversation this
morning, our panelists

00:18:03.150 --> 00:18:05.550
will help us think
through what you could

00:18:05.550 --> 00:18:09.790
call an intersectional analysis
that brings in race, class,

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:13.380
and other social determinants
to give us a fuller

00:18:13.380 --> 00:18:17.800
understanding of what you might
call compounding privileges,

00:18:17.800 --> 00:18:23.100
and also compounding lack
of privilege that influence

00:18:23.100 --> 00:18:25.710
political access and power.

00:18:25.710 --> 00:18:28.470
Martha Jones will speak from
a historical perspective

00:18:28.470 --> 00:18:31.380
about race, gender, and
birthright citizenship.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:34.290
Kari will provide an
overview of the asylum

00:18:34.290 --> 00:18:38.460
process and its problems and
discuss some possible reforms,

00:18:38.460 --> 00:18:41.790
focusing in particular on
the value asylum seekers

00:18:41.790 --> 00:18:43.680
bring to our nation.

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:45.930
And finally, Tali
Mendelberg will

00:18:45.930 --> 00:18:48.930
present her fascinating
research about gender dynamics

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:51.480
in public speech and
group decision making,

00:18:51.480 --> 00:18:55.772
and its implications
for civic engagement.

00:18:55.772 --> 00:18:57.480
I just want to tell
one story, and then I

00:18:57.480 --> 00:18:59.640
will go on to the panel.

00:18:59.640 --> 00:19:03.000
This and the last year, my
son was doing some organizing

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:04.210
at Connecticut.

00:19:04.210 --> 00:19:08.530
And he was doing
the door knocking.

00:19:08.530 --> 00:19:10.410
He was trying to organize
anti-Trump feeling

00:19:10.410 --> 00:19:11.400
into political action.

00:19:11.400 --> 00:19:13.302
By the end, he was
doing door knocking.

00:19:13.302 --> 00:19:14.760
He was knocking on
doors a couple--

00:19:14.760 --> 00:19:16.620
a weekend before the election.

00:19:16.620 --> 00:19:17.910
Knocked on a gentleman's door.

00:19:17.910 --> 00:19:20.160
Happened to be African
American, and I

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:23.940
think that's important to his
appreciation for the rights

00:19:23.940 --> 00:19:25.830
of citizenship, as we'll see.

00:19:25.830 --> 00:19:28.440
At one point in the
conversation my son asks him,

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:30.880
are you going to be
voting on Tuesday?

00:19:30.880 --> 00:19:34.860
And the man looked at my
son very seriously and said,

00:19:34.860 --> 00:19:37.530
it's our job.

00:19:37.530 --> 00:19:40.050
And in many ways,
I think this panel

00:19:40.050 --> 00:19:44.250
is about our job as
citizens, men and women

00:19:44.250 --> 00:19:48.630
committed to equality
and democracy.

00:19:48.630 --> 00:19:50.520
So I'm honored to
be here, honored

00:19:50.520 --> 00:19:52.770
to introduce this discussion.

00:19:52.770 --> 00:19:54.420
After the panelists
speak, I will

00:19:54.420 --> 00:19:57.810
ask some initial questions, and
I will open it up very quickly

00:19:57.810 --> 00:20:01.500
to this distinguished audience.

00:20:01.500 --> 00:20:04.590
And with that, I bring on Kari.

00:20:04.590 --> 00:20:06.220
Bless you all for
being here today.

00:20:06.220 --> 00:20:06.986
Thank you so much.

00:20:06.986 --> 00:20:07.486
Thank you.

