voters, cisgender women

01:39:59.280 --> 01:40:02.070
in the electorate, are
much more likely to gain

01:40:02.070 --> 01:40:05.400
political knowledge and gain
political empowerment when

01:40:05.400 --> 01:40:08.730
they see women in actual,
visible, concrete positions

01:40:08.730 --> 01:40:10.280
of power.

01:40:10.280 --> 01:40:11.500
- And finally, Martha.

01:40:11.500 --> 01:40:14.500
- So if I could, I'll
just come back to briefly

01:40:14.500 --> 01:40:16.840
Priscilla Douglas'
question about tone.

01:40:16.840 --> 01:40:18.820
I appreciate it
very much, because I

01:40:18.820 --> 01:40:24.860
think there's a way in
which we can come back

01:40:24.860 --> 01:40:30.060
to values and morality and
this kind of discourse.

01:40:30.060 --> 01:40:35.810
But it is also true that Jody's
question suggested to me--

01:40:35.810 --> 01:40:38.510
many of us, I'll
say, I am learning

01:40:38.510 --> 01:40:41.180
to do that with a new
kind of nuance, right?

01:40:41.180 --> 01:40:47.180
Which is to say when I invoke
categories like gender,

01:40:47.180 --> 01:40:49.920
like race, the meanings
and the nuances,

01:40:49.920 --> 01:40:53.690
the subtleties, the textures of
those categories have shifted.

01:40:53.690 --> 01:40:57.590
And I have to be mindful of
the transgendered members

01:40:57.590 --> 01:41:00.320
of my community just
as I am aware of men

01:41:00.320 --> 01:41:04.340
and women in my community, or
people who identify as such.

01:41:04.340 --> 01:41:08.930
I find myself using Ta-Nehisi
Coates' somewhat awkward

01:41:08.930 --> 01:41:09.710
phrasing, right?

01:41:09.710 --> 01:41:11.660
People who believe
themselves to be white.

01:41:11.660 --> 01:41:14.510
People who are believed to be
white rather than white people.

01:41:14.510 --> 01:41:17.360
And this is a burden on us.

01:41:17.360 --> 01:41:21.650
I think it's an
imperative on us to speak

01:41:21.650 --> 01:41:26.975
through the sort of tone
that we would call for,

01:41:26.975 --> 01:41:30.740
to insist on the kind
of nuance as well that I

01:41:30.740 --> 01:41:34.730
think is missing from this
particular historical moment.

01:41:34.730 --> 01:41:37.040
So thank you so much
for that question.

01:41:37.040 --> 01:41:37.610
- Thank you.

01:41:37.610 --> 01:41:40.910
I want to close with one
sentence and a quotation.

01:41:40.910 --> 01:41:43.190
The one sentence is I'm
very grateful for what you

01:41:43.190 --> 01:41:45.170
said just a moment ago, Kari.

01:41:45.170 --> 01:41:47.600
Because for at
least three decades,

01:41:47.600 --> 01:41:49.820
I have been obsessed
with a paradox

01:41:49.820 --> 01:41:51.710
in our political
conversation that it's

01:41:51.710 --> 01:41:55.210
the political right that talks
a lot about family values,

01:41:55.210 --> 01:41:56.780
but feminists and
progressives who

01:41:56.780 --> 01:42:00.050
talk the most about what
it takes to make families

01:42:00.050 --> 01:42:02.090
and childrearing work better.

01:42:02.090 --> 01:42:04.970
And somehow, we have to bring
those conversations together,

01:42:04.970 --> 01:42:08.510
or challenge the prevailing--
what family values is

01:42:08.510 --> 01:42:12.650
taken to mean and try to make
it mean something substantive.

01:42:12.650 --> 01:42:15.650
The quotation I can't resist
ending this panel with

01:42:15.650 --> 01:42:17.180
is from somebody
many of you know,

01:42:17.180 --> 01:42:20.870
Rose Schneiderman, the famous
American trade unionist.

01:42:20.870 --> 01:42:24.610
And it seemed appropriate for
an opening panel on citizenship.

01:42:24.610 --> 01:42:27.020
"What the woman who
labors wants is the right

01:42:27.020 --> 01:42:31.550
to live, not simply exist, the
right to life as the rich woman

01:42:31.550 --> 01:42:36.050
has the right to life, and
the sun and music and art.

01:42:36.050 --> 01:42:39.110
You have nothing that the
humblest worker has not

01:42:39.110 --> 01:42:40.940
a right to have also.

01:42:40.940 --> 01:42:45.530
The worker must have bread,
but she must have roses too.

01:42:45.530 --> 01:42:47.510
Help, you women of privilege.

01:42:47.510 --> 01:42:50.240
Give her the ballot
to fight with."

01:42:50.240 --> 01:42:51.240
Thank you, Martha.

01:42:51.240 --> 01:42:52.360
Thank you, Kari.

01:42:52.360 --> 01:42:53.500
And thank you, Tali.

01:42:53.500 --> 01:42:58.050
[APPLAUSE]

